{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656335"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18719"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.13,0.67,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77063"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11451"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10575"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77063"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe penis receives dual autonomic innervation that controls erectile function and ejaculation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the neural control of penile erection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Somatic activation via acetylcholine release","Sympathetic activation via noradrenaline release","Parasympathetic activation via nitric oxide release","Parasympathetic inhibition of smooth muscle","Sympathetic inhibition of blood flow"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic activation via nitric oxide release\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism controlling penile erection. When activated, parasympathetic nerves in the pelvic nerve release nitric oxide, causing relaxation of smooth muscle in the corpus cavernosum and vasodilation of penile arteries. This allows blood to fill the erectile tissue, resulting in tumescence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic activation via noradrenaline release\u003C/strong\u003E - Sympathetic activation actually causes detumescence and is involved in ejaculation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomatic activation via acetylcholine release\u003C/strong\u003E - While somatic nerves control the bulbocavernosus and ischiocavernosus muscles, they are not primarily responsible for erection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic inhibition of smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - While smooth muscle relaxation occurs, it is through active nitric oxide release, not inhibition\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic inhibition of blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - Sympathetic activation promotes vasoconstriction and detumescence, not inhibition of blood flow\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe balance between parasympathetic and sympathetic tone determines the erectile state of the penis, with parasympathetic dominance promoting erection and sympathetic dominance promoting detumescence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parasympathetic activation via the pelvic nerve causes vasodilation and erection through nitric oxide release.","Sympathetic activation via the hypogastric nerve causes detumescence and ejaculation.","Nitric oxide is the key neurotransmitter that mediates penile vasodilation and erection."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:32:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:32:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11451"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77063"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[]